 public school high school team. Because an individual living in the local area has as much contribution to that local school as does a child. More, actually, because the adult actually pays the taxes of which you speak. &#10;Unless the funding formula for the local district in some way compensates the school for the presence of your non-attending child in the district, any services that your child might choose to use at the district actually cost the district money. And that money is effectively being taken from the students who actually attend that school. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="860" language="en" documentId="631" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="stellaluna4" date="Last edited 09/06/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=33" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="631" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="97"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="98" end="224"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="225" end="520"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="521" end="860"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>